{"cursor":"16921","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Malt' is germinated cereal grains that have been dried in a process known as\n\"malting\". The grains are made to germinate by soaking in water, and are then\nhalted from germinating further by drying with hot\nair. [http://www.howtobrew.com/section1/chapter3.html \"How to brew\nmanually'' by John\nPalmer] [http://www.howtobrew.com/section2/chapter12.html\nWhat is malting?] Malting grains develops the enzymes required\nto modify the grain's starches into sugars, including the monosaccharide\nglucose, the disaccharide maltose, the trisaccharide maltotriose, and higher\nsugars called maltodextrines. It also develops other enzymes, such as proteases,\nwhich break down the proteins in the grain into forms that can be used by yeast.\nMalt also contains small amounts of other sugars, such as sucrose and fructose,\nwhich are not products of starch modification but were already in the grain.\n\nMalted grain is used to make beer, whisky, malted shakes, malt vinegar,\nconfections such as Maltesers and Whoppers, flavored drinks such as Horlicks,\nOvaltine and Milo, and some baked goods, such as malt loaf, bagels and rich tea\nbiscuits. Malted grain that has been ground into a coarse meal is known as\n\"sweet meal\". {{cite book |author=Horace Kephart|title=Our southern\nhighlanders|edition=eBook|publisher=The Macmillan Company|location=New\nYork|year=1922|page=134|quote=The sprouted corn is then dried and ground into\nmeal. This sweet meal is then made into a mush with boiling water, and is let\nstand two or three days.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vuNBAAAAIAAJ&pg=P-\nA134#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2011 April 10 }} Various\ncereals are malted, though barley is the most common. A high-protein form of\nmalted barley is often a label-listed ingredient in blended flours typically\nused in the manufacture of yeast breads and other baked goods.\n\nThe term \"malt\" refers to several products of the process: the grains to which\nthis process has been applied, for example malted barley; the sugar, heavy in\nmaltose, derived from such grains, such as the baker's malt used in various\ncereals; or a product based on malted milk, similar to a malted milkshake\n(i.e., \"malts\").\n","linknr":359,"url":"Malting","recorded":1364186504,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Malt&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Malt&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Malt","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Malting&redirect=no","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/File:Sjb_whiskey_malt.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Sjb_whiskey_malt.jpg/220px-Sjb_whiskey_malt.jpg","/wiki/File:Sjb_whiskey_malt.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Milkshake","/wiki/Mucosa-associated_lymphoid_tissue","/wiki/Germination","/wiki/Cereal","/wiki/Germinate","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Enzyme","/wiki/Starch","/wiki/Monosaccharides","/wiki/Glucose","/wiki/Disaccharides","/wiki/Maltose","/wiki/Maltotriose","/wiki/Maltodextrine","/wiki/Proteases","/wiki/Beer","/wiki/Whisky","/wiki/Milkshake","/wiki/Malt_vinegar","/wiki/Malteser","/wiki/Whoppers","/wiki/Horlicks","/wi